<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WWF-UK response to the Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs Committee Inquiry on Food Security</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-size:18pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:73%; margin:14pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt">Written submission from WWF-UK</span></h1><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; font-size:15pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt; padding-bottom:4pt; padding-top:6pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:15pt">6 December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">INTRODUCTION</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">WWF is a leading global conservation organisation, employing over 5,000 staff in more than 100 countries and with more than 5 million supporte</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">rs across the world.  The UK charity</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> - WWF-U</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">K - was launched in 1961.  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We work in partnership with local communities, civil society organisations, governments, multinational agencies and the private sector on the issues of fresh water, biodiversity, climate change, forests, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">marine</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> environment</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, sustainable consumption, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">infrastructure and energy</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Environment, Food &amp; Rural Affairs </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Committee</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’s Inquiry into food security</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Our responses </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">to the issues raised by the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">focus on those areas </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">most </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">relevant to our work.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:14pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY</span></h2><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Natural resources and ecosystems provide the platform for agricultural production, supplying crops and livestock </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">as well as</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> other vital services such as pollination, water regulation, pest control and soil fertility.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The current food system is unsustainable and will become more </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">so</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">as the</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> climate change</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, competition for resources </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">increases </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">and diet</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s change</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> in the global south</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.  It is failing </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">poor people and damaging ecosystems and habitats. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We need to redesign the food and agriculture system to deliver better nutrition</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> poverty reduction, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">safeguard biodiversity, mitigate and adapt to climate change and ensure the planet can support future generations.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Agricultural policy, investments and practice </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">must</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> be informed by a</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">nalysis of</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> a) ecological carrying capacity, including water resource availability</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> b) the potential impact on ecosystem services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> c) the potential impacts on human populations </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> depend on those ecosystem services</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and d) impacts of and on climate change. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 10.06pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Food insecurity is rarely due to production deficiencies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">more usually </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">result</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> a lack of access</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> to nutritious food</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, affordability </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">issues </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">or food being diverted for fuel or animal feed.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RESPONSE</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> TO </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ISSUES RAISED BY THE COMMITTEE</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 12.69pt; padding-left:8.61pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Extremes of hunger and obesity, and high levels of food waste, illustrate the inequality and inefficiency in the food system and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">underline</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> that insufficient overall global food production and supply </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> not the main factor</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> driving food insecurity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 14.11pt; padding-left:7.19pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Food security </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> four dimensions: food availability</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> access</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> utilisation</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and stability. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">An emphasis on availability or supply has led to the assumption that we need to produce more food, but improvements in other aspects of the food system could lead to greater increases in food security. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">WWF would add a fifth dimension</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> environmental sustainability</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and as a result </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">our response focuses on</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">sustainable food security</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 14.03pt; padding-left:7.27pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Is increasing agricultural production the answer to food insecurity? </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In 2009 the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">UN’s Food and Agriculture Organisation (</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">FAO</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> estimated that, based on a ‘business as usual’ scenario, the world may need to increase food production by 70% by 2050 to meet predicted consumption patterns</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">However, the FAO recognise</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“increasing production is not sufficient to achieve food security. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">It must be complemented by policies to enhance access by fighting poverty, especially in rural areas, as well as effective safety net programmes”</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">it has</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> acknowledged that </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">a massive</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> increase in food production will have major undesirable impacts on</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, among other things,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> land use, water</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> biodiversity. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Faced with these prospects, WWF believes there must be greater emphasis on tackling the problems inherent </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the food system, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">loss and waste</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> distribution</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> women’s rights</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> smallholder productivity</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and consumption. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">If these are addressed, the FAO confirms that agricultural production</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> will not need to increase so significantly. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 14.18pt; padding-left:7.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Food security impacts on all areas of human wellbeing, particularly health. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">More than one billion people are undernourished worldwide</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">At the same time 1.6 billion are overweight or obese</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In the United States and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">UK approximately 30% of all food </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">is wasted</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 13.78pt; padding-left:7.52pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">WWF </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">echoes</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the view expressed by the Director-General of the FAO that food insecurity in the UK and the EU is not a function of insufficient food being grown, but rather of a lack of income to buy it.  This problem </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">will not</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> be fixed by growing more food. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 14.19pt; padding-left:7.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The UK Government’s Foresight report into Food and Farming Futures concluded that</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the world’s food production systems are unsustainable. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The authors identified five major challenges:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">balancing future demand and supply sustainably – to ensure that food supplies are affordable;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ensuring that there is adequate stability in food supplies – and protecting the most vulnerable from the volatility that does occur;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">achieving global access to food and ending hunger;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">managing the contribution of the food system to the mitigation of climate change;</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 31.36pt; padding-left:4.09pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">maintaining biodiversity and ecosystem services while feeding the world.</span></li></ul><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 13.49pt; padding-left:7.81pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In order to meet the challenge of food security</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> ensure </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">robust </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">rural incomes and healthy</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> sustainable diets nationally, regionally and globally a </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">whole food system</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> approach is needed. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> This would ensure</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> a variety of crops </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> grown, agricultural diversity </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">was</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> protected and strengthene</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">d and the food produced provided</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the components for a healthy</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> sustainable diet. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 14.52pt; padding-left:6.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This cannot happen in isolation. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The UK and the EU are part of a global food system and need to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">work towards making that system</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">truly sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 14.19pt; padding-left:7.11pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The price paid for food </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">does not</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> represent the cost of producing it in any OECD country. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The current system is based on subsidies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> both direct</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, as</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> through </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> C</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ommon </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">gricultural </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">olicy (CAP),</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and indirect</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> through fuel subsidies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.  There are also</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> tax breaks</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> most noticeabl</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> for the fossil fuel industry, which EU agriculture depends upon for fertili</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ers and energy (globally 30% of energy produced is used by the agricultural sector). </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">he rise of industrial agriculture has impact</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> on ecosystems, soil fertility and pollinators and the roles these play in providing services.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> These result in costs that will </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> to be born</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> by the farmer and ultimately by consumers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 19.44pt; padding-left:1.86pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Currently we produce food from a narrow range of crops and livestock. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">These often rely on complex food chains</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> F</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">or example</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> intensive poultry production relies on imported feed, often from South America, which in turn needs land, water, fertili</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ers and oil</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> impact</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> on ecosystems such as the Cerrado</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> in Brazil,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and on </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">biodiversity.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">There is increasing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> competition for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">resources </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">to produce this limited range of foodstuffs, so</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> costs </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">are driven up </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">and, if we continue to promot</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e a food system that is dependent</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> on foods like meat, dairy and sugar</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> these</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> higher costs</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> will </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">inevitably </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">be born</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> by producers, retailers</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> consumers</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, and by the environment</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> The alternative to this spiral of rising costs is</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> to switch to foods which </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">need</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> fewer inputs </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> meet our nutritional needs</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, as suggested for example by the UK Government’s ‘eatwell plate’.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 17.42pt; padding-left:3.88pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s well as increased consumer costs</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> current diets place a huge burden on our health care system due to rapidly increasing obesity and associated medical problems. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">It was estimated in the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">oresight study on obesity that</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, in 2011,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> this cost the UK taxpayer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">over £4 billion in direct costs and a further £16 billion in indirect ones</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This is clearly unaffordable and needs to be accounted for when looking at the costs associated with food and farming.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food security</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.84pt; padding-left:2.46pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The UK </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">relies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> on the global supply chain for many resources that are key to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> ability to produce food based on the current farming model. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> These include</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> fossil fuels, fertili</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ers, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">mbedded water</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> (all the water needed to produce a product throughout its life cycle)</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and feed. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">There is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">growing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> global competition for all these re</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">sourc</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">es, exacerbated by the global growth of the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Western diet</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">which is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">based on increased </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">consumption of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">livestock product</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">often </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">beyond healthy eating guidelines. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This growth in demand for high input products, coupled with increasing population</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> will inevitably lead to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">higher</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> prices and </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">competition. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This will be exacerbate</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">increasing</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> water scarcity and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the impacts of</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> climate change on vulnerable production systems. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The current food system depend</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">just </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">20 species for the majority of its calories, a very recent phenomenon.  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This has implications for the resilience of the system</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.76pt; padding-left:2.54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">One solution for the UK would be to invest in </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">different</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> ways </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> feeding pigs, poultry and dairy cattle, through </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the use of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">alternat</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">iv</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e crops and food waste.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> Another would be to look at promoting greater species and crop diversity on farms. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Government and its agencies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">promot</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> sustainable diets nationally and work to ensure developing nations benefit from the lessons learnt </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">here to build sustainable, resilient and healthy food systems in their own countries</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.91pt; padding-left:2.39pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">WWF research</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> has demonstrated that in order to have sustainable, resilient food </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">policies</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> we need to look at the whole food system. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">An integrated approach that combines improved production techniques, appropriate technological advances and sustainable consumption is the only way to ensure a sustainable</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">food secure</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> future.  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">usiness as usual is not sustainable, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">given the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">imp</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">lications</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the environment and people’s health</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.5pt; padding-left:2.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">GM technology is a very emotive topic which </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">requires</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> balanced and informed debate. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">WWF gives neither blanket support </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">or opposition to the use of GM crops in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> They are certainly not a panacea, and s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ome have negative unintended consequences for wildlife</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, but i</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">other</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> case</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> there could be net benefits for conservation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.92pt; padding-left:2.38pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> currently available research does</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> not show the benefits </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">of GM crops </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">outweighing the risks. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">A complete assessment of the risks</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> including the need for other inpu</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ts, like pesticides and fertilis</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ers, the impact on pollinators like bees and how a move to a single crop or animal will impact on species diversity and overall resilience </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">– would need to take place in any proposal to grow GM crops</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.  There are </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">social issues to be considered, including who controls the GM seed, the need to purchase specific inputs and how this cost is born</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e by the farmer</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> when moving to a monoculture system</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, the need for a small</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">holder to have to purchase crops and other foods that they would </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">otherwise </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">have grown or raised themselves. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Any assessment </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">would therefore need</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> to look at </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">environmental, social and economic case in </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">the round</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">If</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, following such an assessment,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the benefits</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> were shown to</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> outweigh the risks then the GM crops for which </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">that was the case c</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ould, after testing and assessment, be </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">approved.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.22pt; padding-left:3.08pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Increasing crop yields in the UK is not likely to make a significant contribution to improving </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">global </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">food security. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> Farmers in other countries</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">food insecure</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> when they cannot afford to buy crops or do not have access to growing methods that</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> for example</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> reduce post-harvest loss. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">They would be helped most by being able to increase their yields and reduc</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> risks through better farming techniques that they can implement on their own farm</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, not </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> UK exports.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 19.25pt; padding-left:2.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">It is important to be clear about the relative importance of new technologies and making real systemic changes to how we produce food globally.  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We already produce enough food to feed everybody on the planet</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">one</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> billion </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">people </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">are undernourished. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> W</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e waste about 30% of food</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> feed large amounts </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">food crops to livestock </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">or use them</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">generate</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> energy</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.  This is</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> food that could be eaten by people on land that could </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">use</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> to grow a greater variety of crops for human consumption. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">est we have an obesity pandemic brought about </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> eating too much.  If we worked towards reducing these burdens and growing appropriate crops in the right places, we would not need to increase food production by as much as some groups suggest. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This would also reduce the perceived need for </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">new technological solutions</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can contribute to increased resilience</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.92pt; padding-left:2.38pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We have no comments to make on this point.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning </span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.86pt; padding-left:0.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Climate change is already having an impact on food security, particularly in poor countries. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">It is the poorest people and countries that are experiencing the earliest and most severe impacts </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> climate change and are least resilient to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> effects. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Climate change threatens to </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">undermine, and even reverse, progress made to date on poverty reduction and development</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.84pt; padding-left:2.46pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Food production and availability </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> being </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">affected</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> by altered hydrological cycles and rainfall patterns. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Rising sea levels, increasing temperatures, soil acidification or salinity and flooding will hit hardest in the mega-deltas, which are important areas for food production</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Climate change is predicted to make wet areas wetter and arid areas dryer, resulting in flooding and drought conditions </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">which will </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">pos</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">e major</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> challenges to sustaining food production regimes. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Increasingly rapid movement of both plant and animal diseases is also linked to climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Examples include: viruses such as foot and mouth, bluetongue</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> avian influenza; plant diseases such as those spread by whiteflies; and pests such as diamond back moth. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Climate change also threatens food security by damaging the livelihoods of the poor and reducing their ability to purchase and secure food. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Climate impacts can wipe out food production in a local area</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> driving up prices and pricing the poor out of the food market.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.25pt; padding-left:1.05pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The agricultural sector is a major contributor to global greenhouse gas emissions that are causing climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Worldwide, agriculture is responsible for about a third of these emissions</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[ix]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> from deforestation caused by agricultural encroachment</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[x]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Emissions from agriculture are expected to increase considerably unless action is taken</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[xi]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> The livestock sector in particular is a major contributor to climate change</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[xii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.18pt; padding-left:1.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Agricultural enterprises need to adapt to climate change as well as reduce their own emissions</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[xiii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.32pt; padding-left:0.98pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Currently UK agricultural strategy is not properly taking into account the risk associated with climate change, </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">either</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> domestically </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">or in terms of the risks</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> throughout the supply chain on which UK livestock farmers </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">– and therefore the consuming public – </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">depend. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 19.92pt; padding-left:1.38pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The food system transcends national boundaries and is increasingly reliant on inputs, be it fuel, fertili</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ers, pesticides, seeds </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">or,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> most noticeably</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> feed from other countries and regions. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The obstacle</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> facing farmers are truly global and as such need to be looked at globally. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Water and biodiversity are highlighted below as </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">two</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> of the most pressing problems from a </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">planetary boundary</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and a food and water security perspective. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Water security</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.33pt; padding-left:0.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Reliable, safe and sufficient water is vital for food production and poverty reduction.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> Rivers, lakes and aquifers are the main sources of our freshwater. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In many places these systems are over</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">exploited due to a lack of or weak holistic policy in managing water resources. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Agriculture uses approximately 70% of global water supplies, while the world’s demand for fresh water is projected to increase by over 30% by 2030</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[xiv]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In developing countries 85% of freshwater withdrawals are for agriculture, mainly for irrigation.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Lack of water is already a threat to farmers’ livelihoods and contributes to political instability. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 19.64pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We face a future in which water resources </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">will be</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> increasingly constrained, with </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">consequent</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> impacts on food production. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Globally there needs to be a better system for assessing and managing water risk. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Patterns of international trade and consumption influence the use and availability of water. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> It</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> is used to produce goods which are traded internationally</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">; so-called</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> ‘virtual water’.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Developed countries, including the UK, import many products with a high ‘virtual water’ content or water footprint, often produced in water-scarce developing </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">countries</span><a name="_ednref15"></a><a href="#_edn15">[xv]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Because of this, agriculture cannot be seen purely as a localised issue</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.  P</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">atterns of global trade and consumption </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">influence</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> the impacts of agriculture on ecosystems and poorer populations. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The UK’s own food security partly depends on better water management in those countries from which we source food imports. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">There are also areas of the UK, such as East Anglia, where water security is becoming an issue of increasing concern. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Ecosystem degradation and biodiversity loss</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.67pt; padding-left:0.63pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Natural resources and natural ecosystems provide the platform for agricultural production, supplying the genetic source material for crops</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> livestock</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> and other products (such as timber, medicines, fisheries and textiles)</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">, and other vital services such as pollination, water regulation, pest control and maintaining soil fertility</span><a name="_ednref16"></a><a href="#_edn16">[xvi]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The Millennium Ecosystem Assessment reports that over 60% of ecosystem services are degraded and used unsustainably, with the natural resources critical for livelihood security for the world’s poorest in rapid decline</span><a name="_ednref17"></a><a href="#_edn17">[xvii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">This decline has implications for the sustainabil</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ity and resilience of agricultur</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">al systems</span><a name="_ednref18"></a><a href="#_edn18">[xviii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">In many areas agriculture has become increasingly precarious as soil erosion has increased and soil fertility declined, while productivity has been affected by changes in rainfall. </span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.33pt; padding-left:0.97pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">It is estimated that about three-quarters of the genetic diversity found in agricultural crops has been lost in the last century alone</span><a name="_ednref19"></a><a href="#_edn19">[xix]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Industrial livestock farming </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">uses</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> only five key animal species (</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">attle, chickens, pigs, sheep and goats) and about 100 breeds account for almost all commercial meat and dairy production. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Small-scale farmers and pastoralists maintain 40 livestock species and around 7,600 breeds that contribute to biodiversity and resilience as well as maintaining jobs and food production. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Greater resources should be allocated to improving the productivity of these systems and making them more resilient.</span></li><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.79pt; padding-left:0.51pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Agriculture often drives land use change which leads to biodiversity loss</span><a name="_ednref20"></a><a href="#_edn20">[xx]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> Unsustainable</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> agriculture has contributed to underground water depletion, agrochemical pollution, soil exhaustion and global climate change</span><a name="_ednref21"></a><a href="#_edn21">[xxi]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Conversion of natural habitats for production of food, timber, fibre, feed and fuel </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">a main driver of biodiversity loss. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Worldwide</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> agriculture accounts for 38% of the ice free land surface</span><a name="_ednref22"></a><a href="#_edn22">[xxii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">It has</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> led to the clearance or conver</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">ion </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">70% of the </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">world’s </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">grassland, 50% of </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> savannah, 45% of temperate deciduous forest and 27% of the tropical forest biome</span><a name="_ednref23"></a><a href="#_edn23">[xxiii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing self</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 18.76pt; padding-left:2.54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">We have no comments to make on this point</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; line-height:113%; margin:14pt 0pt 14pt 20.18pt; padding-left:1.12pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">Any food and farming strategy should be based on securing the basic human rights to adequate food and good health, while at the same time reducing the global and local environmental impacts of the food we produce and consume. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">It should not </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">rest</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> on a continuation of the status quo </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">which has given us</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> widespread hunger, ill-health associated with poor diets and increasing environmental degradation. </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt">The underlying causes of inequalities in the food system, such as unfair trade and subsidy systems, need to be addressed to ensure food security for the poor, and to promote sustainable agriculture.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">REFERENCES</span></p><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:113%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> Th</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">ough this prediction has</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> now </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">downgraded </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> suggest </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">we might need to produce a maximum of 60% more food by 2050.</span></p><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> FAO</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> (2009) How to feed the world by 2050 - </span><a href="http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/templates/wsfs/docs/expert_paper/How_to_Feed_the_World_in_2050.pdf"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/tem</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">p</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">lates/wsfs/docs/expert_paper/How_to_Feed_the_World_in_2050.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> The Economist Conference Feeding the World in 2050 Geneva, Switzerland, 8 February 2012</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> Keynote Address by José Graziano da Silva, Director-General of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nat